      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Read all safety warnings, instructions, illustrations, and specifications provided with this power tool. Failure to follow them may result in electric shock, fire, and/or serious injury. Save all warnings and instructions for future reference.
      </div>

      <h3>General</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Keep the work area clean and well lit; do not run the tool in explosive atmospheres (flammable liquids, gases, or dust). Keep children and bystanders away.</li>
        <li><strong>Always wear eye protection</strong> marked to comply with ANSI Z87.1. Use a dust mask, hearing protection, and non-skid footwear as conditions require.</li>
        <li>Prevent unintentional starting &mdash; make sure the trigger is off before inserting the battery, picking up, or carrying the tool.</li>
        <li>Do not overreach; keep proper footing and balance. Do not wear loose clothing, jewelry, or long hair near moving parts.</li>
        <li>Remove the battery pack before making any adjustments, changing accessories, or storing the tool.</li>
        <li>Maintain labels and nameplates &mdash; they carry important information. Contact a Milwaukee service facility for free replacements if missing or unreadable.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Battery</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Recharge only with the specified M12&trade; charger and use only designated M12&trade; battery packs &mdash; other chargers or packs create a risk of fire.</li>
        <li>Keep an unused pack away from metal objects (paper clips, coins, keys, nails) that could short the terminals and cause burns or fire.</li>
        <li>Do not use a damaged or modified pack. Do not expose a pack or tool to fire or temperatures above 265&deg;F (130&deg;C) &mdash; it may explode.</li>
        <li>Under abusive conditions liquid may be ejected from the battery; avoid contact. If contact occurs, flush with water; for eyes, also seek medical help.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Sander-Specific Hazards</h3>
      <div class="danger">
        Finish sanding can produce clouds of fine dust that could ignite in the presence of sparks or open flame. Always wear a suitable dust mask or respirator and work in a well-ventilated area.
      </div>
      <div class="warning">
        Some dust created by power sanding contains chemicals (lead from lead-based paint, crystalline silica from masonry, arsenic and chromium from chemically treated lumber) known to cause cancer, birth defects, or reproductive harm. Work in a well-ventilated area with approved respiratory protection or an OSHA-compliant dust extraction solution.
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Secure the workpiece</strong> before sanding. Unsecured work can be thrown toward the operator.</li>
        <li>Inspect for and remove all raised nails and fasteners before sanding &mdash; striking a fastener can cause loss of control.</li>
        <li>When removing paint or varnish, the solvent/remover must be off the workpiece and the surface completely dry before sanding (fire and explosion risk).</li>
        <li>Use only accessories specifically recommended for this tool.</li>
      </ul>

