      <h2>Assembly</h2>

      <h3>Removing and Inserting the Battery</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        Always remove the battery pack before changing or removing accessories.
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>To remove: push in the release buttons and pull the battery pack away from the tool.</li>
        <li>To insert: slide the pack into the body of the tool until it latches securely into place.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Attaching Hook-and-Loop Sanding Sheets</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Align the sanding sheet with the backing pad, then press the fuzzy side of the sheet firmly against the backing pad.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="note">
        Hook-and-loop sheets can be reused for the life of the abrasive. Keep the backing pad clean for best adhesion &mdash; brush it lightly with a small brush occasionally.
      </div>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always wear eye protection marked to ANSI Z87.1. In dusty situations, wear respiratory protection or use an OSHA-compliant dust extraction solution.
      </div>

      <h3>Fuel Gauge</h3>
      <p>Turn the tool on to check remaining charge &mdash; the fuel gauge lights for 2&ndash;3 seconds.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Below 10% charge: one light flashes 4 times.</li>
        <li>End of charge: one light flashes 8 times and the tool will not run &mdash; charge the pack.</li>
        <li>Battery too hot: the gauge lights flash and the tool will not run &mdash; let the battery cool down.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Using the Speed Selector</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/milwaukee-2531-20/p03_01.jpg" alt="Detail of the speed selector button with the four-position OPM speed indicator on the M12 FUEL detail sander" />
        <figcaption>Press the speed selector to cycle through the four speed settings</figcaption>
      </div>
      <p>Press the speed selector button to cycle through the four speeds. When the desired speed indicator number is lit, begin work. Allow the tool to come to a complete stop before changing speeds.</p>

      <h3>Starting, Stopping, and Controlling Speed</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>To start: grasp the handle firmly and pull the trigger. (An LED turns on when the trigger is pulled and goes off shortly after release.)</li>
        <li>To vary speed: increase or decrease pressure on the trigger &mdash; the further it is pulled, the greater the speed.</li>
        <li>To stop: release the trigger. Ensure the tool has come to a complete stop before laying it down.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Trigger Lock-On</h3>
      <p>Use lock-on when sanding for an extended period or over a large area.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>To lock on: pull the trigger and push in the lock-on button.</li>
        <li>To release: pull and release the trigger.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Selecting Sandpaper and Grits</h3>
      <p>Choose the abrasive material to suit the workpiece:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fine woodwork</strong> &mdash; garnet or aluminum oxide</li>
        <li><strong>Rough woodwork</strong> &mdash; aluminum zirconia or ceramic aluminum oxide</li>
        <li><strong>Manufactured wood products</strong> (particleboard, MDF) &mdash; silicon carbide or aluminum oxide</li>
        <li><strong>Solid surface materials</strong> (Corian&reg;, quartz, granite) &mdash; silicon carbide or aluminum oxide</li>
        <li><strong>Metals</strong> &mdash; emery or aluminum oxide</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Start with a grit just coarse enough to remove high spots and roughness, then step through successively finer grits. Do not jump from a very coarse grit straight to a very fine grit &mdash; the fine grit will not remove the marks left by the coarse grit.</p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Grit</th><th>Type</th><th>Typical application</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>60&ndash;80</td><td>Coarse</td><td>Initial sanding of rough surfaces, fast stock removal, stripping painted and rusted surfaces.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>100&ndash;120</td><td>Medium</td><td>Intermediate sanding and removal of minor surface imperfections.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>150&ndash;180&ndash;220</td><td>Fine</td><td>Fine sanding prior to staining, priming, or sealing.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>General Sanding Technique</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Place the sander on the workpiece <em>before</em> starting it &mdash; starting it off the surface lets the free-floating pad spin fast enough to scratch the work on contact.</li>
        <li>The sander can be moved across the workpiece in any direction (on wood, regardless of grain direction).</li>
        <li>Light pressure for fine work, moderate pressure for rough work. Excessive pressure slows pad rotation.</li>
        <li>Keep the pad flat on the workpiece &mdash; tipping the sander or using the pad edges produces an uneven finish and reduces pad life.</li>
        <li>Keep the sander moving in broad, even strokes. Dwelling in one spot can gouge the surface.</li>
        <li>Check the workpiece frequently &mdash; this random-orbit action works more aggressively than a simple orbital sander.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Removing Paint or Varnish</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove as much as possible with a paint solvent or varnish remover, then scrape away residue with a putty knife and let the surface cool and dry.</li>
        <li>Make sure all solvent/remover is off and the workpiece is completely dry before sanding (fire and explosion risk).</li>
        <li>Use a coarse-grit sheet to help prevent clogging.</li>
        <li>Keep the sander moving over new areas to avoid heating and softening the old coating; work in wide, overlapping strokes.</li>
        <li>As the workpiece shows through, switch to medium grit, then gradually to fine grit, to avoid scratching.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always remove the battery pack before performing any maintenance. Never disassemble the tool, battery pack, or charger &mdash; contact a Milwaukee service facility for all repairs.
      </div>

      <h3>Replacing the Backing Pad</h3>
      <p>The hook-and-loop backing pad can be rotated to 8 positions for ease of use. Replace it if broken or defective.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack and any sanding sheets.</li>
        <li>Remove the screw that holds the backing pad in place.</li>
        <li>Remove the backing pad.</li>
        <li>Clean dust and debris from the sander.</li>
        <li>Install the new backing pad in the desired position and tighten the screw securely. Do not overtighten.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>General Care and Cleaning</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Inspect regularly for undue noise, misalignment or binding of moving parts, and broken parts.</li>
        <li>Clean dust and debris from the vents. Keep handles clean, dry, and free of oil or grease.</li>
        <li>Use only mild soap and a damp cloth. Avoid gasoline, turpentine, lacquer thinner, paint thinner, chlorinated solvents, ammonia, and ammonia-based detergents &mdash; they harm plastics and insulation. Never use flammable or combustible solvents around the tool.</li>
        <li>After six months to one year (depending on use), return the tool, battery, and charger to a Milwaukee service facility for inspection.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="danger">
        Never immerse the tool, battery pack, or charger in liquid or allow liquid to flow inside them.
      </div>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely cause / remedy</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Tool will not run; one fuel-gauge light flashes 8 times</td><td>Battery is fully discharged &mdash; charge the pack.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tool will not run; fuel-gauge lights flash</td><td>Battery is too hot &mdash; allow it to cool down.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tool does not start or lacks power with a fully charged pack</td><td>Clean the contacts on the battery pack; if it still fails, return the tool, charger, and battery to a Milwaukee service facility.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sanding sheet keeps falling off</td><td>Clean the backing pad (brush lightly) for better hook-and-loop adhesion; replace the pad if worn.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Uneven finish or short pad life</td><td>Keep the pad flat on the work; avoid tipping or using the pad edges.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

